		<td width="18"><img src="/Graphics/Interface/Icons/spacer.gif" width=18 height=1 border=0></td>
	
	
		<td>
	




	<font size="-1"><b>Exhibits, Conferences, Keynotes, and Awards Focus on Workstyle Technology</b></font>

	<p>New York, N.Y - Aug, 19 1999
	<BR>
	New workstyle technologies will be unveiled at the 2000 International CES-Your Source for Workstyle and Lifestyle Technology, the first major technology event of the new millennium, to be held January 6-9, 2000 in Las Vegas, Nev.  With a full line-up of exhibits, conferences, keynote addresses and an awards program, CES will highlight all of the latest technologies and products consumers need to work how, when and where they choose. <P>
"Workstyle products give consumers a range of benefits, including convenience and the ability to access information and increase personal productivity while on the go. Wireless phones, palm-tops, notebook computers, mobile Internet access devices, digital cameras and other products allow consumers to work when and where they want to," stated Robbi Lycett, CES vice president. <P>
Attendees can see such new workstyle products as: <P>
Hand-held PC devices -new PDAs and palm-tops from Casio, Philips and others.  <P>
Telephony options - the hottest wireless and landline devices from Alcatel, CIDCO, Ericsson, InfoGear, Lucent, Motorola, Nokia, Nortel, Qualcomm, Samsung, Siemens and others. <P>
Digital imaging - innovative digital cameras, camcorders and scanners from Casio, Gamla, JVC, Kenwood, Pixera Corp., Sony and others. <P>
Home networking - the latest systems from 2-Wire, 3Com, ADSL Forum, Cisco, Intel, Panja, Smart Corp., Sun Microsystems, Vantage, X-10 and others. <P>
Internet-access devices - state-of-the-art non-PC access products from Philips, Sharp, Sony, Websurfer and others. <P>
Most workstyle exhibits at CES will be located in the North Hall of the Las Vegas Convention Center (LVCC), but you'll find workstyle products throughout the other three exhibit venues.  Several exhibit areas in the LVCC also will focus on computer and workstyle-type products: <P>
Mobile Computing Pavilion <P>
Digital Imaging Pavilion  <P>
USB (Universal Serial Bus) Pavilion <P>
SoHo and Y2K Solutions Pavilion <P>
Home Data Networking Pavilion <P>
On Friday, Jan. 7, the hottest workstyle products will be showcased in one place when the CES Workstyle Awards are presented. <P>
To help attendees sort through all of the knowledge they glean from the workstyle exhibits on the show floor, the CES Workstyle Technology Conference Track is geared to help attendees gain insight into the small business industry, the telecommuting market and other ways consumers work today.  Seven in-depth sessions highlight the advances in digital imaging, high-speed Internet access, hand-held information devices and other technologies that enable consumers to work-any time, any way and anywhere they wish.   <P>
In addition to the workstyle track, CES offers a trade and training event for integrated home systems, The Habitech Institute.  The CES Emerging Technology Conference Track and Dataquest Predicts Consumer Technology Conference Track also have workstyle-related sessions that focus on broadband access technologies. Plus, the industry can attend keynote addresses from workstyle visionaries: <P>
Bill Gates, chairman and CEO, Microsoft Corp. <P>
Eric Benhamou, chairman and CEO, 3Com Corp. <P>
Scott McNealy, chairman and CEO, Sun Microsystems <P>
With more than 1,500 exhibitors and 90,000 attendees expected, the 2000 International CES will focus on 25 product areas in the workstyle and lifestyle categories, with more than a dozen exhibit pavilions.  Products showcased will include digital audio and video, information technology, home networking, mobile electronics, wireless communications, content media, delivery systems, e-commerce and accessories.  Product designers and industry representatives will be on hand to demonstrate these cutting-edge products and concepts.    <P>
As the sponsor, manager and producer of the International CES-Your Source for Workstyle and Lifestyle Technology, the Consumer Electronics Manufacturers Association (CEMA) reinvests all profits from CES into industry services, including technical training and education, product promotion, engineering standards development, market research, and governmental and legal affairs support.  As the first major technology event of the new millennium, the 2000 International CES is the launch pad for 21st century technology. <P>
CEMA is a sector of the Electronic Industries Alliance (EIA), the 75-year-old Arlington, Virginia-based trade organization representing all facets of electronics manufacturing.  CEMA represents more than 500 U.S. manufacturers of audio, video, accessories, mobile electronics, communication, information technology and multimedia products that are sold through consumer channels.    <P>
